country_country_legislature: Parliament of the Republic of Ghana
country_seat_numbers_notes:
https://www.parliament.gh/committees.php and https://www.parliament.gh/mps?leadership for assembly leaders
Per Article 128 of the1992 Constitution of Ghana, the Supreme Court shall consist of the Chief Justice not less than nine judges. https://judicial.gov.gh/index.php/supreme-court-judges. Per Article 76, the Cabinet shall be constituted by not less than 10 and not more than 19 ministers of state. However per article 78 there is no ceiling for Ministers

Per Article 128 of the1992 Constitution of Ghana, the Supreme Court shall consist of the Chief Justice not less than nine judges. https://judicial.gov.gh/index.php/supreme-court-judges. Per Article 76, the Cabinet shall be constituted by not less than 10 and not more than 19 ministers of state. However per article 78 there is no ceiling for Ministers

party_notes: This party is an organization to support and fulfill reunification policies of Worker's Party of Korea. In Dutch law, it is prohibited for a judge to test the constitution (art. 120 constitution). Therefore, no judges are included in the dataset.

party_notes: The party is the successor party of the Popular Front of Moldova (1989-1992), and the Christian Democratic Popular Front (1992-1999) - all staunch supporters of the unification with Romania. party_name: Alliance of Builders of Islamic Iran
party_notes: The Alliance of Builders of Islamic Iran , usually shortened to Abadgaran, is an alliance of some conservative Iranian political parties and organizations. The alliance, mostly active in Tehran, won almost all of Tehran's seats in the Iranian Majlis election of 2004 and the Iranian City and Village Councils elections, 2003. Mahmoud Ahmadinejad, former mayor of Tehran (who is chosen by Tehran's City Council) and now President of Iran, is considered one of the main figures in the alliance.

party_notes: The Combatant Clergy Association (Jame'e-ye Rowhaniyat-e Mobarez) or (جامعه روحانیت مبارز in Persian), is a political party in Iran. It is a pragmatic-conservative clerical party, and was the majority party in the fourth and fifth parliaments after the Islamic revolution. http://rohaniatmobarez.com

party_notes: The Association of Combatant Clerics (Persian: مجمع روحانیون مبارز; majma'-e rowhāniyūn-e mobārez, also translated as the Assembly of Combatant Clerics, and Combatant Clerics League) is a reformist Iranian political party. It was established on March 16, 1988. It is not to be confused with the Combatant Clergy Association (Persian: جامعه روحانیت مبارز) which is a conservative political party. http://rouhanioon.com/

party_notes: National Trust Party (Persian: حزب اعتماد ملی) , also translated as National Confidence Party, is an Iranian political party based on reformist and populist message. NTP was established in 2005 by former Parliament speaker Mehdi Karroubi following his controversial defeat in 2005 presidential election. The party also publishes a newspaper of the same name (Etemad-e Melli), which was banned by the Iranian judiciary on August 16, 2009 after the newspaper reported Karroubi's claims that some election protesters were raped while in custody

As for Supreme Court leaders, there was very little information on 4 of them (but I have created profiles for them anyway) and almost no information on the remaining three. However, their names and positions were provided in Sources/Notes box under each profile of Supreme Court leader.
MP's Salary: In Uzbekistan, the Chairmans of both Houses receive 3.5 million Uzbekistani Soms (about $ 450) a month. Deputy Chairmans - 3.2 million Uzbekistani Soms (415 dollars), ordinary deputies - 2.9 million Uzbekistani Soms (about 376 dollars). In addition to these salaries, deputies receive different kinds of incentives, the amounts of which are not disclosed.
Source: https://www.pnp.ru/in-world/2017/04/18/deputatskie-zarplaty-v-stranakh-centralnoy-azii-nakhodyatsya-pod-grifom-sekretno.html
Electoral System: In accordance with the Constitution of the Republic of Uzbekistan, the Majority Election System is applied in the country, which is based on the absolute and qualified vote of the majority.
Source: http://navoi.biz/news/2014-12-14-501-987

The Best Party started as a joke to respond to the poor shape of politics in Iceland in the wake of the financial crash of 2008. The party ran for municipal elections in Reykjavik in 2010 and earned 7 out of 15 seats in City Council. Party leader Jon Gnarr, best known as a comedian and filmmaker, became Mayor as the Best Party formed a coalition majority with the Social Democratic Alliance.

The Movement is a shoot-off from the Civic Movement which was established in the wake of the financial crash in Iceland in 2008. Running for seats in all six districts in Iceland, the Civic Movement got four MPs elected (out of 63 seats) in the April 2009 elections. One left the party within a few months and serves as an independent MP. The other three MPs left the party in September of 2009 and formed The Movement, for which they serve in Parliament.

party_notes: Indian Union Muslim League (IUML) is a state political party in the state of Kerala ,India. The chief support base of the party falls inside northern and central Kerala. Note that since the name 'Indian Union Muslim League' is registered at the Electoral Commission by a splinter-group of the party, the party contests elections as the Muslim League Kerala State Committee.

country_country_ppltn_source: World Bank, United States Census Bureau
party_notes: Mizoram People's Conference, a regional political party in Mizoram, India. MPC was formed by Brig Thenphunga Sailo on April 17, 1975. Sailo is the party chairman and was the chief minister of Mizoram from 1979 to 1984. Thenphunga was an army officer and then a Human rights Activist before starting his Political Party.

country_country_ppltn_source: World Bank, United States Census Bureau
party_notes: Mizo National Front (MNF) is a regional political party in Mizoram, India. MNF emerged out of the Mizo Famine Front, which was formed by Pu Laldenga to protest against the inaction of the Indian central government towards the famine situation in the Mizo areas of the Assam state in 1959. It staged a major uprising in 1966, followed by years of underground activities. In 1986, it signed the Mizo Accord with the Government of India, renouncing secession and violence. MNF suffered a strong incumbency wave in the 2008 Mizoram Election and lost all their MLA seats except three.

country_country_ppltn_source: World Bank, United States Census Bureau
party_notes: The Manipur Peoples Party (MPP) is a political party in the Indian state of Manipur. MPP was founded on December 26, 1968 by a group of dissidents from the Indian National Congress. At the February 2007 Manipur state elections, the party received 5 of the 60 seats

country_country_ppltn_source: World Bank, United States Census Bureau
party_notes: Maharashtrawadi Gomantak Party (MGP) was Goa's first ruling party after the end of Portuguese colonial rule in 1961. In the first elections held after India took over the former Portuguese colony, it ascended to power in December 1963 and stayed on, till being ousted from power by defections in early 1979.

party_notes: The Jharkhand Vikas Morcha (Prajatantrik) is a state political party in the state ofJharkhand , India . The party formed by former Jharkhand chief minister Babulal Marandi. The name of the party roughly translates to 'Jharkhand Progress Front (Democratic)'. The party's formation was announced by Marandi at Hazaribagh on 2006-09-24. Marandi was earlier a member of the Bharatiya Janata Party, but he quite in mid 2006 because he felt he was being sidelined in the party.

party_notes: The UDA is a coalition of three parties( the Liberia National Union-LINU; Liberia Education and Equal Rights Party-LEAD and Reformation Alliance Party-RAP) that contested the 2005 General and Presidential Elections. Its Presidential candidate, John S. Morlu, I(Uncle to the Auditor General of Liberia, John S. Morlu, II) won 1.2% of the valid votes cast. The party won one seat in the House of Representatives. Today, LINU is headed by Cllr. Winston Tubman who contested the 2005 Elections as Standard Bearer of the National Democratic Party of Liberia, party of the late President Samuel Doe of Liberia.

party_notes: Due to the political crisis that linked many politicians to illegal far-right wing forces, this Party, also known as PIN, was founded to give a political platform to other politicians supported by former members of other parties linked with these political scandals. Its result at the legislative elections on March 2010 were seen as a surprise to Colombia's public opinion. The Party received one million votes approximately. The Party is not officially part of the President Santos' coalition government because of its members scandals with far right wing forces, but they remain very close to the former and current political establishment so they could be considered as closer to the coalition political initiatives than an opposition party to the government. Having said this this party will be labeled in this project as part of the coalition government even if they are not as an official or formal part of it.

party_notes: Seimas: 16 National Resurrection Party is a centre-right, political party in Lithuania. At the legislative elections of 12 October 2008 (Lithuanian parliamentary election 2008) the party won 15.09% of the popular vote and 13 seats. In the second round the party won 3 additional seats taking up 16 seats in total. The party currently participates in a new governing coalition, along with Homeland union and Liberals' Movement of the Republic of Lithuania which gained a combined governmental majority of 72 out of 141 seats in the seimas, led by Andrius Kubilius. The Party is headed by a former Lithuanian performer and producer Arūnas Valinskas who was the Speaker of Seimas until Sept. 2009.

party_name: Liberals' Movement of the Republic of Lithuania

party_notes: Seimas: 8 The Liberal and Centre Union is a centre-right, liberal, and conservative liberal [1], political party in Lithuania, and a member of the Liberal International and the ELDR. It was formed in 2003 by a merger of the Liberal Union of Lithuania (Lietuvos liberalų sąjunga), the Centre Union of Lithuania (Lietuvos centro sąjunga) and the Modern Christian-Democratic Union (Moderniųjų krikščionių demokratų sąjunga). The combined party is led by Gintautas Babravičius. In the 2004 European Parliamentary Elections it gained 11.2% of the vote and returned 2 MEPs. At the last legislative elections, 10 October 2004, the party won 9.1 % of the popular vote and 18 out of 141 seats in the Seimas. At the legislative elections of 2008 the party lost heavily gaining only 8 seats out of its previous 18 and 5.34% of the national vote, leaving the party continuing its tenure in opposition.

party_name: Electoral Action of Poles in Lithuania
party_notes:

Seimas: 1 The New Union (Social Liberals) (Lithuanian: Naujoji sąjunga (socialliberalai), or NS, is a centre-left, social liberal party in Lithuania. The NS is member of the European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party and is an observer at Liberal International. It was founded in 1998 and is led by Artūras Paulauskas. Its policy is based on the social liberal ideology, the principal values of which are personal freedom, social solidarity, welfare of people and justice. In 2000 it formed a coalition government with the Liberal Union, and in 2001 a new coalition with the Social Democrats and later on in 2004 a coalition with the Social Democratic Party of Lithuania and the Labour Party which lasted until 2008. Its candidate Vilija Blinkevičiūtė won 16.6 % of the votes at the presidential elections of 13 June 2004. At the last legislative elections, 10 October 2004, the party won 11 out of 141 seats. At the legislative elections of 2008 the party lost heavily, gaining only 1 seat in the Seimas from its previous 11 and only 3.64 percent of the national vote and due to its coalition partner, Labour Party also losing heavily its coalition with the former and the Social Democratic Party of Lithuania collapsed and a new centre-right coalition, led by Andrius Kubilius, who becomes prime minister for a second time, of Homeland Union, National Resurrection Party, and Liberals' Movement of the Republic of Lithuania which gained a combined governmental majority of 72 out of 141 seats, took over, leaving the party in opposition.

At the 2000 legislative elections, the party 2 out of 269 seats in the National Assembly. In the presidential elections of the same day, its candidate John Momise Cheyo won 4.2% of the vote.The party didn't field a presidential candidate in either the 14 December 2005 election or 31 October 2010 elections, but did win one seat in National Assembly elections held in 2005 and 2010. This is one of the weakest opposition parties in Tanzania.

National Assembly of the Socialist Republic of Vietnam
party_notes: The Vietnamese Communist Party was formally dissolved in 1945 in order to hide its Communist affiliation and its activities were folded into the Marxism Research Association and the Việt Minh, which had been founded four years earlier as a common front for national liberation. The Party was refounded as the Vietnam Workers' Party (Đảng lao động Việt Nam) at the Second National Party Congress in Tuyen Quang in 1951. The Congress was held in territory in north Vietnam controlled by the Việt Minh during the First Indochina War. The Third National Congress, held in Hanoi in 1960 formalized the tasks of constructing socialism in what was by then North Vietnam, or the Democratic Republic of Vietnam (DRV) and committed the party to carrying out the revolution of liberation in the South. At the Fourth National Party Congress held in 1976, the Worker Party's of North Vietnam was merged with the People's Revolutionary Party of South Vietnam to form the Communist Party of Vietnam

country_country_legislature: National Assembly of the Socialist Republic of Vietnam
party_notes: The People's Revolutionary Party was a political party in South Vietnam established on January 1, 1962. It provided leadership for the Việt Cộng uprising. The party foundation was publicly announced by Radio Hanoi on January 18, 1962. The stated goals of the party was to combat imperialism, feudalism and colonialism. The party was not an explicitly communist party, but according to the January 18 Radio Hanoi broadcast, it represented the Marxist-Leninists in South Vietnam, and was led by a Central Committee, often referred to as 'Central Office, South Vietnam' (COSVN). The smallest organizational unit of PRP was the cell. 1-7 cells constituted a "chi bộ", the party was the leading force in the National Liberation Front (NLF). Both at national and local levels party committees lead the NLF work. In the Central Committee there were three main responsibilities, Military Commissar (coordinating the relations with the North Vietnamese Army), NLF control and general administration.Vo Chi Cong was party's chairman. In 1976, the party was merged with the Worker's Party of North Vietnam to form the Communist Party of Vietnam.

party_notes: The Democratic Party of Vietnam (Đảng Dân chủ Việt Nam) was a political party in North Vietnam and the Socialist Republic of Vietnam. It was founded on 30 July 1944 to unite petty bourgeoisie and intelligentsia. It joined Vietminh. From 1954 to 1975, it was active in North Vietnam and from 1975 to 1988 in the re-unified Vietnam. It supported the line of the Communist Party of Vietnam and became in effect its puppet party. It was a member of the Vietnamese Fatherland Front and was represented in the Vietnamese parliament and government, its leader was Nghiem Xuan Yem. The party (along with the other 'non-communist' party in Vietnam, the Socialist Party) was disbanded in 1988 (as was the Socialist Party of Vietnam). In 2006, a dissident organization with the same name - Democratic Party of Vietnam - was established

party_notes: All Nigeria Peoples Party is a conservative political party in Nigeria. At the last the 2003 general election, the party won 27.0% of the popular vote and 92 out of 360 seats in the House of Representatives and 27 out of 109 seats in the Senate.The ANPP is the household party in the extreme north of Nigeria, primarily due to its mass appeal.In the 21 April 2007 Nigerian National Assembly election, the party won 62 out of 360 seats in the House of Representatives and 16 out of 109 seats in the Senate. It is the strongest opposition party, controlling seven of the nation's thirty-six states.

party_notes: This is a classical liberal Nigerian political party. The party emerged after the first general election in the fourth republic, that is the party was formed via the merger of the Alliance for Democracy, the Justice Party, the Advance Congress of Democrats, and several other minor political parties in September 2006. In the 2007 general election the party The Party has strong presence in the South West (1 Governor, 3 Senators and 2 State Houses), Mid-West (1 Governor) and North Central Regions (3 Senators). Lagos, Edo, Ekiti, Kogi, Ondo, Bauchi, Plateau, Niger, Adamawa, Oyo and Osun states by far accounts for majority of the party's presence and discernable power base.

party_notes:
The majority of Jordanian politicians are elected as independents without any party affiliation, in the last elections (2016) only 22 candidates representing 7 parties were elected to the lower house (the Chamber of Deputies), which totals 130 representatives.
http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2016/09/jordan-legislative-elections-winners-losers.html

https://www.albawaba.com/news/islamic-action-front-wins-15-seats-making-it-largest-bloc-jordan-parliament-885880

The Islamic Action Front is considered the political wing of the Muslim Brotherhood in Jordan, however over the years there has been substantial fracturing within the group (both the Muslim Brotherhood and the IAF) which has led to three distinct Islamist groups winning seats in the Chamber of Deputies.

Zamzam is a breakaway group from the Islamic Action Front (which is seen as the political wing of the Muslim Brotherhood in Jordan), as such sometimes the 5 Zamzam deputies are counted with the IAF. See http://www.jordantimes.com/news/local/zamzam-leaders-discuss-plans-projected-political-party and http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/09/jordan-parliament-spearhead-political-change-160926054613800.html
Also known as National Congress Party

More moderate than the IAF, ICP (more commonly referred to as Wasat or Hizb al-Wasat) is not associated with the Muslim Brotherhood and actually disagrees with some of their standpoints.http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/09/jordan-parliament-spearhead-political-change-160926054613800.html and https://www.alaraby.co.uk/english/indepth/2016/9/19/independents-vs-parties-polls-to-test-jordans-electoral-reforms

party_notes: Oromo Peoples' Congress (OPC) is one of the main opposition parties in Ethiopia founded in 1996 under the name of Oromo National Congress (ONC)by Dr. Merera Gudina, its current chairman. The party was part of the United Ethiopian Democratic Forces (UEDF) in 2005 national elections and has formed a coalition with the Oromo Federalist Democratic Movement (OFDM)in January 2009.

country_country_legislature: House of People's Representatives (Yehizbtewekayoch Mekir Bet)
party_name: Union of Tigrayans for Democracy and Sovereignty
party_notes: Union of Tigrayans for Democracy and Sovereignty (also known as ARENA Tigray)is founded in the early 2000's by Dr. Gebru Asrat, a former president of Tigray Region. After leaving the regional party (TPLF) and the ruling party (EPRDF), he founded ARENA Tigray as an alternative party to TPLF in Tigray. In 2008, ARENA Tigray has merged with other opposition parties to form MEDREK (officially known as the "Forum for Democratic Dialogue in Ethiopia". MEDREK contested the national election of 2010 and won a single seat in the lower house, representing an electoral district in Addis Ababa.

party_notes: Bicameral, but Upper House is indirectly elected

CoD was formed after the high profile departure of Ben Ulenga from SWAPO in 1999 (Hopwood, G.,Guide to Namibian Politics 2008). This party is not dominated by a certain ethnic group in its composition and as such it could be safely assumed that it is not centred on a specific significant social group. CoD have 1 seat in the National Assembly.
Bicameral, but Upper House is indirectly elected

RP joined the DTA on its formation in 1977 and remained under DTA until 2003, when it registered with the Directorate of Elections as a separate political party (Hopwood, G., Guide to Namibian Politics 2008). RP is viewed, and righly so, as a party for whites. RP have 1 seat in the National Assembly.

NDMC is quite a minute party and commands less support. Even though its President is also a Traditional Leader of the /Gobanin Damara community (see Hopwood, 2008), one could not safely argue that its composition is ethnic based. NDMC is not represented in the National Assembly.

party_name: National Unity Democratic Organisation of Namibia (NUDO)

party_notes: MAG support base largely derives from Namibian-Afrikaaners. MAG is not represented in the National Assembly.
The NDP was formerly known as Caprivi National Democratic Party. NDP is not represented in the National Assembly.

DPN was formed in 2008 in the Southern part of Namibia and contested the 2009 National Assembly and Presidential Elections (see www.namibian.com.na/index.php?id=28&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=46280&no_cache=1). Its support base is predominantly Nama-speaking Namibians.
"Konsensus Bebas" is an official platform for independent MPs to present issues in Parliament

party_name_local: Malay: Persatuan Cina Malaysia, Traditional Chinese: 馬來西亞華人公會
Pertubuhan Pasok Momogun Kadazandusun Murut Bersatu

party_notes: It was a part of the Barisan Nasional ruling coalition since Sarawak joined the Federation of Malaysia until 2004. In 2010, SNAP officially joined the People's Pact opposition coalition. Although defines itself as multi-ethnic party, the bulk of its members are ethnic Dayaks.
Since Wee Choo Keong, his founder and former president left the party in 2008 to join the PKR (and later become independent), the MDP has been inactive in Malaysian politics

country_countrynme_alt: Official Name: Republic of the Philippines (Republika ng Pilipinas)
country_seat_numbers_notes:
The 321 MP statutory seat count based on the 24 seats allocated for nationally-elected members of the Senate, 238 seats allocated for legislative district representatives to the House of Representatives, and 59 seats allocated for party list representatives to the House of Representatives.
Party list Representatives (representatives from national, regional and sectoral parties or organizations or coalitions) comprise 20% of the total number of the members of the House of Representatives. There are currently 59 party-list representatives.


2016 Senatorial Election Results: https://www.comelec.gov.ph/?r=2016NLE/Resolutions/nboc_res00716
2016 Party List Election Results: https://www.comelec.gov.ph/?r=2016NLE/Resolutions/nboc_res00816

Notes on Department Secretaries (Ministers)
- Confirmed appointments: http://comappt.gov.ph/images/pdfiles/pending/CABSEC_DUTERTE_oct5_new.pdf
- PCOO (Presidential Communications Operations Office) not consider as minister, as it is merely a public information office of the Office of the President
- Individuals yet to be confirmed as secretaries are still included
- This may need updating as the appointment of some individuals have yet to be confirmed

Executive Position includes President and Vice President

party_notes: The Iraqi National Alliance was formed in August 2009 to contest the 2010 Iraqi parliamentary election. It is mainly composed of the following political parties: the Supreme Islamic Iraqi Council (ISCI), Badr Organisation, Sadr Movement, National Reform Trend (Islah), Islamic Virtue Party (Fadhilah), Hezbollah Movement in Iraq, Iraqi National Congress (INC).

The Kurdistan Alliance was initially created to run in the Kurdistan Regional Government parliamentary election in July 2009.Its largest parties are: Kurdistan Democratic Party, Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, Kurdistan Communist Party, the Islamic Movement of Kurdistan, Kurdistan Toilers' Party, Kurdistan Socialist Democratic Party and Turkmen Brotherhood Movement.

party_notes: For the 2010 Iraqi parliamentary elections the Iraqi Accord Front consisted of the following political blocs: Iraqi Islamic Party, General Council for the People of Iraq, and Turkmen Justice Party.

The Unity Alliance of Iraq is a coalition formed to contest the 2010 Iraqi parliamentary elections, it consisted of the following parties: Iraq Awakening and Independents National Alliance, Iraqi Constitution Party, Charter Gathering, Republican Gathering, and some independent candidates.

is one of the political parties created in Egypt after the 2011 Egyptian Revolution. It has an ultra-conservative Islamist Salafist ideology, which believes in implementing strict Sharia law. The party was formed by the former head of the Virtue Party,General Adel Abdel Maksoud; he left the Virtue Party after allegedly discovering a plot which changed the moderate principles of the party. [5] In the 2011–12 Egypt parliamentary elections, the Authenticity party ran on the platform of the Islamist Bloc led by Al-Nour Party, another Salafist party. The Islamist Bloc received 7,534,266 votes out of a total 27,065,135 correct votes (27.8%). The Islamist Bloc gained 127 of the 498 parliamentary seats contested, second-place after the Muslim Brotherhood's Freedom and Justice Party. The authenticity party received 3 of these 127 seats.

The Wafd Party ("Delegation Party) was a nationalist liberal political party in Egypt. It was said to be Egypt's most popular and influential political party for a period in the 1920s and 30s. During this time it was instrumental in the development of the 1923 constitution, and supported moving Egypt from dynastic rule to a constitutional monarchy, where power would be wielded by a nationally-elected parliament.[1] The party was dissolved in 1952, after the 1952 Egyptian Revolution.

Al-Wasat was founded in 1996 when several young but well-respected members of the Muslim Brotherhood broke away from the organization to form a political party. Abu al-‘Ila Madi took charge of the newly formed party and was assisted by fellow Brotherhood defectors Salah ‘Abd al-Karim and Essam Sultan. The party’s religious ideology is drawn from the Wasatiyya (Centrist) school of thought, a liberal interpretive tradition in Islamic thinking that is firmly anchored in Islamic law but seeks to interpret its principles in a manner consistent with the values of a liberal democratic system.

The Building and Development Party (al-Banna’ wa al-Tanmiyya) is the official political party of the Egyptian al-Gama’a al-Islamiyya (the Islamic Group). It was founded by the prominent Islamist Tareq al-Zumr following the January 2011 uprising.

The Egyptian Liberation Party is a new Islamist party with a strong Sufi influence. The party was founded by Ibrahim Zahran following the January 2011 uprising and gained the support of a number of prominent Sufi leaders, including Mohamed Ala’a al-Din Abu al-Azayem of the Azamiyya Sufi Order. The Egyptian Liberation Party was a member of the liberal Egyptian Bloc alliance but left on October 16. It is currently a member of the Completing the Revolution Alliance.

The Freedom and Justice Party was formed by the Muslim Brotherhood in May 2011 and is the dominant Islamist party in Egypt. Aware of the fears that surround its participation, the party defines itself as a “civil” party rather than an Islamic one and has formed the Democratic Alliance with a number of liberal and leftist parties.

Al-Nour is a Salafi political party founded after the January 2011 uprising. It was originally a member of the Democratic Alliance, but left the alliance in September 2011, becoming the founding member and largest party in the Islamist Alliance.

The Free Egyptians Party is fast emerging as a major player. With 100,000 registered members, it is probably second only to the Freedom and Justice Party in terms of its organization and potential. The Free Egyptians Party is the linchpin of the Egypt Bloc.

The Nasserist Party was formally licensed in 1992 under the leadership of Diaeddin Daoud after a decade-long legal battle with the Political Parties Committee and other government institutions. The Nasserist Party endorses Arab nationalism, socialism, and other ideals associated with the 1952 revolution. The party has modeled itself after Nasser’s Arab Socialist Union and still adheres to key documents that emerged from the nationalist revolution, including the National Covenant and the 30 March Program of 1968. The party’s aging chairman, Daoud, passed away on April 6, 2011 after dominating the party for nearly two decades and refusing to relinquish his leadership position despite challenges from younger party members who blamed him for the party’s stagnation. On April 23, 2011, Sameh Ashour, former First Vice President of the party, was elected president of the Party during a party conference. At the same conference, Ahmed Hussein, the party’s secretary general was removed from his position and his party membership was revoked after accusations of complicity with the Mubarak regime.

The al-Tagammu Party was established in 1976 by former Free Officer Khaled Moheiddin. A diverse coalition of former Nasserites, Marxists, and Arab nationalists, al-Tagammu advocated the establishment of a socialist society through the process of popular participation. The party has since moderated its position and lost the support it once had among intellectuals, labor union leaders, and workers. In an attempt to reverse the party’s declining fortunes, in 1984 al-Tagammu tried to reach out to Islamist constituencies. After the fall of the Soviet Union and the decline of socialism worldwide, it took a more conciliatory attitude toward the old regime and was allowed to win five seats in the 2010 elections. After the uprising, the party is still struggling to find its niche.

Al-Adl is a new party seeking to carve for itself a centrist position and a role as a bridge between the Islamist-dominated Democratic Alliance and Islamist Alliance, and the liberal-dominated Egypt Bloc. It is seeking to create a “Third Way” coalition which is yet to be announced. So far, the Egyptian Current Party and al-Wasat were the only other parties that have shown interest in joining the Third Way Coalition, and neither had joined by the candidate registration deadline on October 24th. The party has been critical of the polarization of politics and of the participation in elections of former members of the National Democratic Party.

he Reform and Development Party, a relative newcomer to Egypt’s political scene, was launched in January 2009 by Anwar Tal’at Esma’t Sadat, a nephew of former President Anwar Sadat, after he defected from the Democratic Front Party. The Political Parties Committee rejected his application for legal status in July 2010. Rather than appealing the decision, Sadat started lobbying for a complete overhaul of the committee’s structure to prevent it from functioning as an instrument of the National Democratic Party (NDP) and custodian of the regime’s interests. The party was legalized on May 21, 2011 after the 2011 uprising. In June 2011, the Reform and Development Party merged with the Our Egypt party led by Ramy Lakkah, and Lakkah became the party’s new president.

The Socialist Popular Alliance Party was founded in March 2011 following the January 2011 uprising. A number of the party’s members were formerly members of the al-Tagammu Party, but split from al-Tagammu because of disagreements over the November 2010 parliamentary elections and the January 2010 uprising. Previous al-Tagammu members include Abd al-Ghaffar Shukr and Ibrahim al-Esawi, both prominent Egyptian leftist thinkers.

Al-Karama, a leftist pan-Arab, nationalist, Nasserist party, was founded in 1996 by Hamdeen Sabahi, a former parliamentary representative of the Democratic Arab Nasserite Party, who had defected from the group over disagreements with its then president, Diaeddin Daoud. Al-Karama has socialist tendencies and calls for political pluralism. During the Mubarak era, the party denounced the government for monopolizing political power and restricting the activities of opposition groups. After the January 2011 uprising, al-Karama allied with the Freedom and Justice Party–led Democratic Alliance and was one of the few secular parties to remain in the coalition at the time of the People’s Assembly election.

The party was established in 2011, after the uprising that ousted Hosni Mubarak, by Mohamed al-Sawy, the founder of al-Sawy Culture wheel, a cultural organization that is home to some of Egypt’s most active art and culture centers, book fairs, and concerts. Al-Hadara joined the Democratic Alliance and was one of the few secular parties to remain a member of the alliance at the time of elections. It won two seats of parliament in the 2011 People’s Assembly elections, one of which went to al-Sawy.

The Egypt Civilization Party is a small, centrist, secular political party that describes itself as being “in the center: in the right wing economically, and left wing socially.” It strongly emphasizes culture, the arts, and renewing Egypt’s civilization. It is part of the Democratic Alliance.

party_notes: La ideología del PARTIDO PATRIOTA es democrática y liberal, se fundamenta en la Constitución Política de la República. El fin político del PARTIDO PATRIOTA y sus integrantes es la libertad, la prosperidad, la seguridad y la paz. El carácter de la nación que aspiramos es de unidad, solidaridad y justicia; la piedra angular de la acción política del partido, lo constituye su esencia patriótica y el centro de su esfuerzo en la persona humana. Cree en la libertad como ausencia de la coacción arbitraria, en la persona humana como sujeto y fin del orden social en pleno estado de derecho. El PARTIDO PATRIOTA concibe la política como un medio legítimo y válido para el acceso al poder en beneficio de la nación y sus habitantes. (Source: Party webpage. http://www.partidopatriota.com.gt)

Ideología: Socialismo, Progresismo, Antiimperialismo; Posición: Izquierda
Unicameral; Convergencia CPO-CRD es un partido político guatemalteco de izquierda, identificado profundamente con el Socialismo y el Antiimperialismo. Tiene sus raíces las organizaciones guerrilleras involucradas en el conflicto armado interno ocurrido en la segunda mitad del siglo XX. Anteriormente se llamó Alternativa Nueva Nación.

El Tribunal Supremo Electoral declaró en octubre de 2018 que están analizando la cancelación del partido por posibles delitos electorales.1
Historia
Los orígenes del partido se remontan a los militantes de las Fuerzas Armadas Rebeldes (FAR), grupo guerillero protagonista del Conflicto Armado Interno que posteriormente se aglutinó con otras organizaciones insurgentes para conformar la Unidad Revolucionaria Nacional Guatemalteca (URNG).

Para las elecciones generales de 1999 la URNG, constituida como un partido político legal, junto a los partidos Desarrollo Integral Auténtico (DÍA) y Frente Democrático Nueva Guatemala (FDNG) forman la coalición denominada Alianza Nueva Nación. El líder guerrillero y antiguo dirigente de la URNG, Jorge Ismael Soto, conocido por su nombre de guerra Pablo Monsanto aglutinó a un grupo de miembros del partido que estaban en desacuerdo con el rumbo que había tomado la organización para fundar un nuevo proyecto político bajo el nombre de la mencionada coalición de izquierda. Durante el año 2003 se conforma oficialmente la ANN, como la convergencia de varios disidentes de la URNG y de los comités pro formación de los partidos Solidaridad Democrática (PSD) y Unidad de Izquierda Democrática (UNID). En las elecciones de ese año participa únicamente en las elecciones municipales y legislativas.2​

Elecciones de 2007
El secretario general del partido, Pablo Monsanto, fue proclamado candidato presidencial para las elecciones generales de 2007 junto al empresario Mariano Portillo como vicepresidenciable. Dado su pobre desempeño electoral, al quedar en duodécimo lugar de la intención de voto con 0,57 % del total de votos, la ANN fue cancelada como partido un años después por no alcanzar el umbral mínimo de votos para mantenerse vigente.2​

Posteriormente, se inscribe el partido Alternativa Nueva Nación en 2010 con la misma estructura e ideología de Alianza Nueva Nación, cambiando ligeramente su simbología y reforzando sus bases a lo largo del país.3​

Elecciones de 2011
En las elecciones generales de 2011 la ANN participó en la coalición de partidos de izquierda Frente Amplio, aunque ninguno de sus principales miembros fue postulado a cargos de elección popular. La coalición impulsa la candidatura del binomio formado por Rigoberta Menchú junto a Aníbal García, obteniendo un 3,27% de los votos válidos, quedando en sexto lugar de la intención de voto.4​5​

Después de la disolución de la coalición, la ANN quedó sin representación en cargos públicos.

Unicameral; The party was established in 2011 by Maurico Redford. Prior to the 2015 elections it nominated Alejandro Giammattei as its presidential candidate; Giammattei finished fourth in a field of fourteen candidates with 6% of the vote.[1] In the Congressional elections the party received 2% of the vote, winning two of the 158 seats; [2] Raul Romero Segura in Guatemala City and Claude Harmelin de Leon in Guatemala Department. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuerza_(political_party) www.fuerza.org.gt

Stephen M. Joyce: There are 16 bloques (banks or blocks or caucuses). According to Article 51 of the current version of the Ley Orgánica del Orgáno Legislativo (*Reformado por el Artículo 28, del Decreto Del Congreso Número 14-2016 de fecha 04 de febrero de 2016), statutorily each bloque in the legislature should have only one jefe (chief) and one subjefe (assistant chief).
 
"Artículo 51. Jefatura de Bloque. Cada bloque legislativo elegirá a un jefe
y un subjefe de bloque, comunicándolo a la Junta Directiva del Congreso.
Si durante el transcurso del año legislativo se produce algún cambio en la
Jefatura o Subjefatura de bloque, deberá comunicarse a la Junta Directiva
del Congreso, para su conocimiento."

The actual numbers do not match the statutory numbers, and it is not because there are any vacant MP seats. Some bloques actually have two subjefes (UNE, UCN, PAN, FCN-NACION), some have no subjefes (PU, URNG, WINAQ, FUERZA) and the bloque of "independent" MPs (independientes) does not have a jefe or subjefe. If we count only each jefe then statutorily there should be 16 jefes, but actually there are 15 jefes. When counting subjefes, statutorily there should be 16, but actually there are 15. If we count jefes and subjefes as leadership then there should be 32 Party Leaders. In actuality there are 30 Party Leaders. 

ASSEMBLY LEADERS: 
Statutory=9+7+114+6=136
Actual=9+7+97+6=119
Junta Directiva: 1 Presidente; 3 Vice-Presidentes; 5 Secretarios; Statutory=Actual=9
Junta de Jefes de Bloque: Statutory=16; Actual=15 (not counted in total here)
Comision Permanente: Statutory=7; Actual=7 [acts in the place of the congress when congress is not in session; President of congress is automatically a member, 16+1(Presidente)]
Comisiones Ordinarias:  Statutorily=114; Actual=97 [each of these ordinary committees has statutory status; statutorily each has a Presidente, Vice-Presidente, and Secretario (Artículo 35. Directiva de Comisión), but not all comisiones have these; 8 lack both a vicepresidente and secretario, 1) Vivienda, 2) Trabajo, 3) Derechos Humanos, 4) Finanzas Públicas y Moneda, 5) Gobernación, 6) Reformas al Sector Justicia, 7) Pueblos Indígenas, 8) Juventud; 1 lacks a vicepresidente, Salud y Asistencia Social]
Comisiones Especificas: Statutory=3; Actual=3
Análisis del dictamen de la iniciativa 5311 que contiene reformas al Decreto Número 51-92 del Congreso de la República, Código Procesal Penal.
Has a Presidente, Vice-Presidente, and Secretario

Expediente 2951-2017, para el análisis del segundo párrafo del artículo 407 "N" del Decreto Número 17-73 del Congreso de la República, Código Penal
Has a Presidente, Vice-Presidente, and Secretario

A la vez, obtiene otros Q5 mil por dietas si asiste a sesiones de las comisiones de trabajo donde es integrante, por lo que hace un total de Q29 mil 150. El Congreso cuenta con 158 diputados.

Stephen M. Joyce: There are 16 bloques (banks or blocks or caucuses). According to Article 51 of the current version of the Ley Orgánica del Orgáno Legislativo (*Reformado por el Artículo 28, del Decreto Del Congreso Número 14-2016 de fecha 04 de febrero de 2016), statutorily each bloque in the legislature should have only one jefe (chief) and one subjefe (assistant chief).
 
"Artículo 51. Jefatura de Bloque. Cada bloque legislativo elegirá a un jefe
y un subjefe de bloque, comunicándolo a la Junta Directiva del Congreso.
Si durante el transcurso del año legislativo se produce algún cambio en la
Jefatura o Subjefatura de bloque, deberá comunicarse a la Junta Directiva
del Congreso, para su conocimiento."

The actual numbers do not match the statutory numbers, and it is not because there are any vacant MP seats. Some bloques actually have two subjefes (UNE, UCN, PAN, FCN-NACION), some have no subjefes (PU, URNG, WINAQ, FUERZA) and the bloque of "independent" MPs (independientes) does not have a jefe or subjefe. If we count only each jefe then statutorily there should be 16 jefes, but actually there are 15 jefes. When counting subjefes, statutorily there should be 16, but actually there are 15. If we count jefes and subjefes as leadership then there should be 32 Party Leaders. In actuality there are 30 Party Leaders.

party_notes: Unicameral; The Patriotic Party (Spanish: Partido Patriota, PP) was a conservative political party in Guatemala. It was founded on 24 February 2001 by retired Army General Otto Pérez Molina. Strongly compromised by corruption cases, the party fell from 36% support in 2011 to 4% in 2015. It is dissolved on court order in January 2017
This party was founded in the run-up to the 2007 elections, with Nobel Prize winner Rigoberta Menchú as its presidential candidate.

party_name: WINAQ - Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity - MAIZ (coalition)
party_name_local: WINAQ - Unidad Revolucionaria Nacional Guatemalteca - URNG - MAIZ

party_notes: The Guatemalan Republican Front was founded by former president and dictator Efraín Ríos Montt in 1989 and formally registered in 1990.

Unicameral; conservative populist; Renewed Democratic Liberty (Spanish: Libertad Democrática Renovada, Spanish acronym: LIDER, alternative translations: Democratic Freedom Revival,[3] Renewed Democratic Liberation[4]) was a centre-right political party in Guatemala.[4]

It was founded as a parliamentary group by defectors from the then governing National Unity of Hope party of President Álvaro Colom in 2008.[4] It was officially registered as a political party in 2010. At the end of the 2007-2011 legislature, the Independent Renewed Democratic Liberty parliamentary bloc included 25 out of the 158 deputies in the Congress of the Republic,[5] where it formed a parliamentary alliance with the conservative Grand National Alliance (GANA).

On July 25, 2016 the party was cancelled by the Supreme Electoral Court due to constant breaking of the Electoral and Political Parties Law.[6]

Unicameral; Visión con Valores (VIVA) es un partido político de Guatemala. Fundado en 2007 por Harold Caballeros1​ en donde fungió como secretario general. VIVA es un movimiento social, cimentado en un partido político, con una ideología de Visión a largo plazo y Valores, basada en el republicanismo clásico. Cuenta con representatividad en los 22 departamentos del país.2​ Su propuesta se basa en la Visión a largo plazo y el aspecto moral como rector del comportamiento del hombre, la familia, la sociedad y por supuesto el gobierno.

El 8 de abril VIVA presentó el Plan 2050, que consiste en un modelo de desarrollo para Guatemala, de acuerdo a sus ventajas competitivas y el uso adecuado de los recursos que posee, tomando como referencia los valores y la cultura.3​ Cuenta con el apoyo del Centro de Estudios e Investigaciones para el Desarrollo de América Latina (CEIDAL) en el diseño, elaboración, auditoría y medición de la implementación de políticas públicas.

El Tribunal Supremo Electoral declaró en octubre de 2018 que están analizando la cancelación del partido por posibles delitos electorales.4​
Unidos por Guatemala
El 23 de noviembre de 2010 se oficializó una alianza cívico-electoral entre Visión con Valores (VIVA) y el partido Acción de Desarrollo Nacional (ADN).5​ Esta iniciativa buscó integrar a varias agrupaciones políticas para trabajar con una agenda legislativa en conjunto a manera de darle prioridad a iniciativas de ley de urgencia nacional.

Recientemente fue electo como Secretario General el Ingeniero Armando Castillo.

Coalición VIVA-EG
El 6 de marzo de 2011 se anunció una coalición entre Visión con Valores (VIVA) y el partido Encuentro por Guatemala (EG) dirigido por la parlamentaria Nineth Montenegro. Ambas agrupaciones corrieron juntas en los comicios de septiembre de 2011, obteniendo 274,957 votos y logrando seis diputaciones y cinco alcaldías.

La alianza no trascendió el proceso electoral ya que ambos partidos decidieron legislar desde bancadas separadas, y dos de sus diputados dejaron el partido, Jorge Adolfo de Jesús García Silva	se unió a TODOS mientras Pedro Gálvez Hernández se unió al PRI, quedándose en el mismo únicamente Manuel Alfredo Villacorta Mirón.

Alianza PP
El 18 de septiembre de 2011 a través de una conferencia de prensa, Harold Caballeros hizo público el apoyo al Partido Patriota (PP) para la segunda vuelta electoral. Recalcando que su apoyo es condicionado a la ejecución de planes que compartían similitud entre ambos planes de gobierno, no representando una aceptación ni mucho menos ideales compartidos.6​

Harold Caballeros fue designado como Ministro de Relaciones Exteriores, enfrentándose así a los retos de inmigración, re-establecer las relaciones diplomáticas con otros países y re-estructurar el Ministerio. Caballeros dejó el puesto en 2012.

party_name: Plan Progress for Bolivia - National Convergence (PPB-CN)
party_notes: PPB-CN is a coalition of parties formed in 2009 to compete in the December 2009 elections as the anti-reform right. The coalition includes: Plan Progress for Bolivia (lead by José Luis Paredes, former prefect of La Paz), National Convergence (an Evangelical party formed in 2006 for the constituent assembly elections), Autonomy for Bolivia (Autonomía Para Bolivia, led by Luis Alberto Serrate Middagh), Nationalist Revolutionary Movement (Movimiento Nacionalista Revolucionario founded in 1941, led by Guillermo Bedregal Gutíerrez), and New Republican Force (Nueva Fuerza Republicana founded in 1993, lead by Manfred Reyes Villa). Reyes Villa is the leader of the coalition.
Centrist/Leftist party that has experienced minimal success in elections.

Founded in 1999 to complete in mayoral race in La Paz, MSM established an alliance with MAS for the 2009 elections. MSM broke the alliance in 2010 to complete independently in the La Paz mayoral elections. MSM members in the lower chamber have since separated from MAS. MSM identifies as a left-of-center party.

country_country_legislature: Assembly of the Representatives of the People
country_seat_numbers_notes:
Note on ministers: the Chahed Cabinet was inaugurated on 27 August 2016. In the beginning it had 24 ministers. Then one of them was removed. Currently there are 23 minister posts but only 21 ministers because 2 of them were replaced by 2 other ministers who are currently holding 2 offices. 
Note on Supreme court:  The constitutional court judges, they will be nominated on December, 2017.   In the meantime, the court of cassation is acting as the supreme court in the country until the nomination of the constitutional judges. I created a profile for the president of the court of cassation who has been recently nominated (last June), and who will be acting as the supreme judicial authority in the country till the official establishment of the constitutional court.

Vice-President of the Riigikogu, chairman of a committee and chairman of a faction – 0.85
President of the Riigikogu – 1

party_notes: It was formed to fight for equality for the smaller isle of Tobago.
It split from the National Alliance for Reconstruction in 1988. Their ideology is mostly concerned about democratic socialism, social-democracy, and the Third Way.
It split from the United National Congress in 2006. Their ideology is concerned mainly about democratic socialism, social liberalism, social democracy, and the Third Way.
It was formed as a response to the white people-managed state.

country_seat_numbers_notes:
There are 42 members in the House of the Representatives and 31 members in the Senate. There are two executives who are the President and the Prime Minister of Trinidad and Tobago; they are in the Apex. and in Top 10 list as well. There are 26 Ministers and all of them are either members of the Senate or the House of the Representatives. 
Trinidad and Tobago has a two-party system, which means that there are two dominant political parties, with extreme difficulty for anybody to achieve electoral success under the banner of any other party. This means that there are two party leaders: main party and the opposition coalition party.
There are no assembly leaders in Trinidad and Tobago.
There are 13 Supreme Court members.
P.S. Salaries of MPs are presented by previous coder. Sources of the aforementioned information are provided in the coder profile (Sources/Notes box).

party_notes:
Official Website: http://www.pnm.org.tt/
PNM is largely supported by the Afro-Trinidadian population of the country, and most of its members are of Afro-Trinidadian descent.
Today, politics is still divided on ethnic lines, with the People’s National Movement supported by Afro-Trinidadians and the People’s Partnership coalition supported by Indo-Trinidadians. But socially, the groups are mingling more—and increasingly intermarrying. Nearly a quarter of the population identifies as mixed-race.

The People's Partnership is a political coalition in Trinidad and Tobago among four political parties: the United National Congress, the Congress of the People, the Tobago Organization of the People, the National Joint Action Committee. Its currents political leader is the Hon. Kamla Persad-Bissessar.
Ideology:	Democratic socialism, Social democracy, Third Way
Political position: Centre-left

party_notes: The Socialist Party founded by the first President of Senegal Léopold Sedar Senghor, ruled the country from 1960 to 2000. Its former name was the Senegalese Progressive Union (1958-1976). In 1976, he joined the Socialist International. During the 2001 legislative elections, the PS receives 326,126 votes, or 17.4%, and won 10 seats on the 120 then the National Assembly of Senegal.The PS is one of the parties who chose to boycott the legislative elections of 2007. Its first secretary was one of the leading figures of the opposition Senegalese.

party_notes: The party operates in exile and is considered the liberal party of Equatorial Guinea. The party is a member of Liberal International.

country_country_ppltn_source: Statistical Office of the Republic of Slovenia
country_seat_numbers_notes: Executive power is exercised by the Government of Slovenia. Legislative power is vested in the National Assembly and in minor part in the National Council. The National Council (Slovene: Državni svet) is according to the Constitution of Slovenia the representative of social, economic, professional and local interest groups in Slovenia and has a legislative function working as a corrective mechanism of the National Assembly, although it does not itself pass acts. It may be regarded as the upper house, but the bicameralism is distinctively incomplete.

The National Council (Slovene: Državni svet) is according to the Constitution of Slovenia the representative of social, economic, professional and local interest groups in Slovenia and has a legislative function working as a corrective mechanism of the National Assembly, although it does not itself pass acts. It may be regarded as the upper house, but the bicameralism is distinctively incomplete.

country_seat_numbers_notes:
Official website of the Parliament of Fiji: http://www.parliament.gov.fj/members-of-parliament/
MP's actual note: There are 50 members shown in the official website of the Parliament of Fiji. The reason why I coded 49 members is that one of the members (Isoa Tikoca) was accused of corruption and suspended from the Parliament.
There are 2 executives: President and Prime Minister.
Currently, there are 13 Ministers in the Cabinet. Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cabinet_of_Fiji
There are 3 parties that are currently represented in the Fijian Parliament, and hence three party leaders.
There is one Assembly leader in Fiji and she is the current Speaker of the Parliament of Fiji - Jiko Luveni.
Source: http://www.parliament.gov.fj/speaker-of-parliament/
There are 9 supreme court judges (including the Chief Justice) in the Supreme Court of Fiji. Source: http://www.judiciary.gov.fj/index.php/supreme-court/judges
MP salary source: http://fijisun.com.fj/2015/10/15/analysis-should-mps-get-more-than-50000-a-year/

party_notes: The United Peoples Party is a political party whose support base lies chiefly among General Electors - Fiji Islanders who belong to ethnic minorities, such as Europeans, Chinese, Banaban Islanders, as well as multiracial people. Since 2001, its president and parliamentary leader has been Mick Beddoes, the sole member elected from the party to the 71-member House of Representatives in the general election that year, when it won 0.5 percent of the vote. The party claims to follow moderate, centrist policies.

Unicameral: Fiji has only one house.
Source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Federation_Party
Ideology	Social democracy
Third way
Federalism

The Fijian Political Party (better known by its initials SVT, which stand for its Fijian name, Soqosoqo ni Vakavulewa ni Taukei) is a party which dominated politics in the 1990s and was the mainstay of coalition governments from 1992 to 1999, but which is currently without representation in the House of Representatives. The party was founded in 1990 as the political vehicle of the Great Council of Chiefs, with the declared goal of uniting all indigenous Fijians. A new constitution promulgated in 1990, following two military coups in 1987, abolished the "national" parliamentary seats elected by universal suffrage (which had comprised almost half the House of Representatives); all members henceforth were to be elected by enrolled voters on "communal" electoral roles that were limited to specific ethnic communities, each of which had an allocated number of seats in the House (37 indigenous Fijians, 27 Indo-Fijians, 1 Rotuman, and 5 General Electors (Europeans, Chinese, Banaban Islanders, and other minorities). The end to multiracial voting resulted in a trend towards intracommunal politics, and multiracial parties like the old Fijian Alliance of longtime Prime Minister Ratu Sir Kamisese Mara were therefore dissolved and replaced by parties representing principally a single ethnic group. Ratu Mara had announced his intention not to contest the election that was to be held in 1992, but his wife, Ro Lady Lala Mara, a chief in her own right as the Roko Tui Dreketi, or Paramount Chief of Burebasaga, one of three hierarchies to which all Fijian chiefs belong in the House of Chiefs, seemed a natural choice to lead a new party as the successor to his. In addition to the Great Council of Chiefs, the powerful Methodist Church also endorsed the party.

In addition, the statutory assembly leader is one (1), not 31 because it does not reflect the regulations of Congo's constitution. It should be updated accordingly.

The Parliament of Bhutan (Dzongkha: རྒྱལ་ཡོངས་ཚོགས་ཁང་ gyelyong tshokhang) consists of the King of Bhutan together with a bicameral parliament.This bicameral parliament is made up of an upper house, the National Council and a lower house, the National Assembly.
https://www.revolvy.com/main/index.php?s=List%20of%20political%20parties%20in%20Bhutan

The Parliament of Bhutan (Dzongkha: རྒྱལ་ཡོངས་ཚོགས་ཁང་ gyelyong tshokhang) consists of the King of Bhutan together with a bicameral parliament.This bicameral parliament is made up of an upper house, the National Council and a lower house, the National Assembly.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhutanese_National_Assembly_election,_2013

The Bhutan Communist Party (Marxist–Leninist–Maoist) is a banned communist party in Bhutan.

The CPB (MLM) calls for a New Democratic Revolution and the overthrow of the Bhutanese monarchy and the House of Wangchuck. Its armed wing is the Bhutan Tiger Force. It is currently estimated to have 600 to 1000 cadres.The party is banned by the Bhutanese government.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhutan_Communist_Party_(Marxist%E2%80%93Leninist%E2%80%93Maoist)

The Bhutan National Party is a former Bhutanese political party formed to contest the Himalayan nation's 2008 general election. The party was an alliance of former civil servants, defense officials and businessmen.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhutan_National_Party
This party was formed and is based in exile

The Druk National Congress was formed in exile in Kathmandu, Nepal on June 16, 1994.

On August 26, 2010, Bhutanese political parties in exile formed an umbrella group to pursue a "unified democratic movement led by Rongthong Kunley Dorji, President of the Druk National Congress. The group's offices opened in Kathmandu in November 2010, and it seems to receive some measure of support from the Nepalese government

There will be a constitutional court which is not installed yet (although the provision is there since the 1990s), so currently the Hof van Justitie (Court of Justice) is the highest court in Suriname, with a President a deputy president and at most 15 other members (art. 32 regulation of the Surinam Judicial Power).
Note (1) Assembly leaders and coded number do not align since some MPs are chairs of several committees. 
Notes about variance between coded and statutary members of the supreme court:

It is unclear how many members there actually are, but according to the law there is a president, a vice president and 15 other members at most. So, the seat statutary number I coded as 17 and since there is no source stating how many members there actually are (and I have not received a response to this question) I have coded the actual number of judges as 17 (art. 32 regulation of the Surinam Judicial Power).
Beside the lack of sources for how many members there actually are, there are no sources that include the names of the judges of the Court of Justice if a judge is mentioned in a news report for example it unclear whether this judge is still a judge of the high court because most of these news reports are several years old. 
Now I was only able to code the president and vice president of the court of justice. However, it remains unclear how many other judges there are and who these judges are. 
Note that these president and vice presidents are mentioned first in the art. 133 of the constitution: The Judiciary consists of the President and the Vice President of the Court of Justice, the members and deputy members of the Court of Justice, the Procurator General of the Court of Justice, two Attorneys General and the other members of the Public Prosecution Department (sub 1). The president, the vice-president, the members and the deputy members of the court of justice are the judicial power with the power of jurisdiction.
